Not by acts only, but by constant speeches, full at once oi grimness and humor, did Cato struggle against the degeneracy of his time.¹ He concluded his period of office with a sels-lau- datory hai-angue, and assumed the title Censorius, while his statue was placed in the temple of the goddess Salus with an inscription affirming that he had reformed the Roman nation.
